{"title_page": "Mahdi al-Modarresi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n[[Sayyid]] '''Muhammad-Mahdi al-Husayni al-Modarresi''' (b. 1977), also known as '''Sayed Mahdi al-Modarresi''', is an [[Iraqi Australians|Iraqi-Australian]] [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Religious scholar|scholar]], [[author]] and [[orator]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.modarresi.org/english/biography.htm|title=Sub-site: Sayyid Mahdi al-Husayni al-Modarresi: Brief Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=Office of Sayed Hadi Al-Modarresi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>{{Infobox religious biography\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Sayyid]]\n| name               = Muhammad-Mahdi Al-Modarresi\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| image_upright      = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0647\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a\n| native_name_lang   = ar\n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_date         = 1977\n| birth_place        = [[Kuwait City]], [[Kuwait]]\n| nationality        = Australian\n| other_names        = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = \n| father             = [[Hadi al-Modarresi]]\n| relatives          = [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi]] (uncle) <br /> [[Ali Akbar al-Modarresi]] (uncle) <br /> [[Mortada Al-Qazwini|Murtadha al-Qazwini]] (great uncle)\n| website            = {{official website|www.modarresi.org/english/index.htm}}\n|background=#ABE9CC}}\n\nHe comes from a distinguished family of scholars which includes supreme religious jurists, such as [[Grand Ayatollah]] Sayyid [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi|Muhammed-Taqi al-Modarresi]], one of Iraq's leading faith leaders of its majority Shia population. He has led prayers at the United States [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]], and delivers lectures around the world. al-Modarresi is an expert in interfaith relations, he leads Interpath, a unique outreach program designed to strengthen ties between Muslims and other major faith traditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/author/sayed-mahdi-almodarresi/|title=Sayed M. Modarresi|last=|first=|date=|website=Huffington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://cdn.minderoo.com.au/content/uploads/2019/02/17100902/GFN-2-Dec-Vatican-Book-digital.pdf|title=A United Faith Against Slavery|publisher=The Minderoo Foundation|year=2014|isbn=|location=Vatican CIty|pages=8|language=en}}</ref> \n\n== Early life and education ==\nal-Modarresi was born in [[Kuwait City|Kuwait]] in 1977. From his father's side, he is the son of [[Hadi al-Modarresi]], and great grandson of [[Mahdi Hussaini Shirazi|Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.modarresi.org/biography/index.html|title=al-Sirah al-Thatiya|last=|first=|date=|website=Office of Sayed Hadi Al-Modarresi|language=ar|trans-title=Biography|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> From his mother's side he is the grandson of Hashim al-Qazwini, and the great grandson of Muhammad-Sadiq al-Qazwini. He claims [[Sayyid|descent]] from the Prophet [[Muhammad]], through [[Ali ibn Husayn Zayn al-Abidin|Ali Ibn al-Husayn]] from his father, and [[Musa al-Kadhim]], from his mother.\n\nUnder his father's supervision, al-Modarresi followed a solid traditional curriculum in the [[hawza]], studying classical works on various disciplines of Islamic jurisprudence as well as the instrumental faculties commonly taught at religious learning institutions. A graduate of the acclaimed al-Qaim Theological Research Institute near the [[Sayyidah Zaynab Mosque]] in Damascus, al-Modarresi reached the level of Sotouh al Ulya (Upper Foundations). His classical curriculum embodied a methodology which crystallizes the middle way of Islam; respect for the differences between jurists, and a spiritual education drawn from the Qur'an and the traditions of [[Prophet Muhammad]] and his Household; the [[Ahlulbayt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nudba.com/wp/speakers/sayed-mahdi-modarresi/|title=Sayed Mahdi Modarresi|website=Nudba.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nHe also undertook his early academic education in the [[United States]], finally studying sociology, politics, and philosophy at tertiary level in [[Australia]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Activism ==\nal-Modarresi has criticised the atrocities committed by the Bahraini government against its people (namely the Shia), especially after the [[Bahraini uprising of 2011|uprising of 2011]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2010/09/10/bahrains-shia-crackdown/|title=Bahrain's Shia crackdown|last=Sotloff|first=Steven|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> He believed that the country's mass uprising, was the result of many decades of abuse. al-Modarresi was also agitated by the West's silence to the situation in Bahrain, and writes in one his articles:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/the-staggers/2012/02/regime-bahrain-protesters|title=Isn't it time we backed Bahrain's revolution?|last=|first=|date=|website=NewStatesmen|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><blockquote>\"Whether western leaders decide to cut their losses or keep the Bahraini government on life support for the time being, by far the worst thing they can do is bury their heads in the sand and assume everything is going to be all right... Imagine the consequences if the western powers had sided with the Hosni Mubarak regime or that of Colonel Gaddafi until the very end... Had it not been for Saudi military support and the West\u2019s political backing, the truth is that this unelected [[House of Khalifa|Al Khalifa]] regime would have collapsed long ago\"</blockquote>al-Modarresi has also criticised [[Saudi Arabian government|Saudi Arabia]] and [[House of Saud|Al Saud]] for its human right's violations, and even so as to compare the regime to [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]], claiming the only real difference between ISIS and the Saudi regime is that the latter has 'made it', having secured a seat at the [[United Nations|UN]] and employ an army of flamboyant diplomats and lobbyists roaming the corridors of [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster Palace]] and [[Capitol Hill]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/sayed-mahdi-almodarresi/a-regime-known-for-its-re_b_11162286.html|title=A Regime Known for {{sic|It|'s|nolink=y}} Recklessness Just Made a Very Reckless Move|last=|first=|date=|website=Huffington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nal-Modarresi authored his first book in 1992, at the tender age of 15. This was a book in Arabic titled, \"About the Signs of Allah and His Greatness\". He later authored two more books in Arabic that were published in Beirut. His last Arabic book was an in-depth analytical study of the prophetic narration known as [[Hadith al-Thaqalayn]], which looks into the practical implications of this controversial narration and provides a thorough insight of the Shia-Sunni deliberations on this text.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109115447/http://ahlulbayt.tv/enlight/?page_id=6|title=Authors \u00ab Enlight Magazine|date=2013-11-09|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nIn the second decade of 2000, al-Modarresi shifted his attention to writing in English, and has published three books which are: \n\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Hajj: Rules and Rituals|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1515186021|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Our Beliefs: The Fundamental Tenets of Islam|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-0994240934|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The Lost Testament: What Christians Don't Know About Jesus|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en|asin=B01K170MDQ}}\n\nHe has also written a collection of essays regarding the contemporary challenges facing Muslim youth, with emphasis on problems which are more relevant in Western nations where they are a growing minority. Such 'taboo' subjects, such as pornography, alcohol, sex, drugs, and religious extremism are discussed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109115750/http://ahlulbayt.tv/enlight/?p=284|title=Raising a Family in the West \u00ab Enlight Magazine|date=2013-11-09|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Lectures==\nal-Modarressi delivers lectures worldwide on traditional as well as contemporary Islamic issues and has lectured in countless mosques, churches, universities, and seminaries across the globe. He has been interviewed by numerous news platforms and has appeared on TV and radio programs such as the BBC. An ardent advocate of interfaith dialogue,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109121823/http://ahlulbayt.tv/enlight/?p=545|title=Interfaith Dialogue at St. Andrew's \u00ab Enlight Magazine|date=2013-11-09|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> al-Modarresi engages in such events on a regular basis and has consistently spoken out against acts of terror.<ref>[http://www.modarresi.org/audio/english/ashura_attack.mp3 BBC's Reporting Religion Interviews - Sayed Mehdi al-Modarressi]</ref> He has also been adamant on directing the world's attention to the [[Arba'een Pilgrimage|Arbaeen pilgrimage]], calling the whole world to try and understand Hussein, his message, and his sacrifice, for this would allow them to begin to understand the ancient roots of ISIS and its credo of death and destruction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/sayed-mahdi-almodarresi/arbaeen-pilgrimage_b_6203756.html|title=World's Biggest Pilgrimage Now Underway, And Why You've Never Heard of it!|last=|first=|date=|website=Huffington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Sznajder|first=Micha\u0142 Jacenty|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SzMlDwAAQBAJ|title=Metropolitan Commuter Belt Tourism|date=2017-05-18|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=|isbn=978-1-317-06067-3|location=|pages=217|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/episode/6vv6gGxsWXxSOsc3619BuL|title=Husayn Means Beauty: The Attraction of the Seventh Century Martyr (1 of 2) (ENCORE) - Progressive Spirit|website=Spotify|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[http://www.modarresi.org/english/index.htm al-Modarresi's Official Website]\n*[https://twitter.com/sayedmodarresi Twitter page] (In English)\n*[https://twitter.com/thesayed Twitter page] (In Arabic)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Modarresi, Mahdi}}\n[[Category:Shia Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n\n[[Sayyid]] '''Muhammad-Mahdi al-Husayni al-Modarresi''' (b. 1977), also known as '''Sayed Mahdi al-Modarresi''', is an [[Iraqi Australians|Iraqi-Australian]] [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Religious scholar|scholar]], [[author]] and [[orator]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.modarresi.org/english/biography.htm|title=Sub-site: Sayyid Mahdi al-Husayni al-Modarresi: Brief Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=Office of Sayed Hadi Al-Modarresi|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = [[Sayyid]]\n| name               = Muhammad-Mahdi al-Husayni Al-Modarresi\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| image_upright      = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0647\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a\n| native_name_lang   = ar\n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_date         = 1977\n| birth_place        = [[Kuwait City]], [[Kuwait]]\n| nationality        = Australian\n| other_names        = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = \n| father             = [[Hadi al-Modarresi]]\n| relatives          = [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi]] (uncle) <br /> [[Ali Akbar al-Modarresi]] (uncle) <br /> [[Mortada Al-Qazwini|Murtadha al-Qazwini]] (great uncle)\n| family             = Al Modarresi\n| website            = {{official website|www.modarresi.org/english/index.htm}}\n}}\n\n\nHe comes from a distinguished family of scholars which includes supreme religious jurists, such as [[Grand Ayatollah]] Sayyid [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi|Muhammed-Taqi al-Modarresi]], one of Iraq's leading faith leaders of its majority Shia population. He has led prayers at the United States [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]], and delivers lectures around the world. al-Modarresi is an expert in interfaith relations, he leads Interpath, a unique outreach program designed to strengthen ties between Muslims and other major faith traditions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/author/sayed-mahdi-almodarresi/|title=Sayed M. Modarresi|last=|first=|date=|website=Huffington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://cdn.minderoo.com.au/content/uploads/2019/02/17100902/GFN-2-Dec-Vatican-Book-digital.pdf|title=A United Faith Against Slavery|publisher=The Minderoo Foundation|year=2014|isbn=|location=Vatican CIty|pages=8|language=en}}</ref> \n\n== Early life and education ==\nal-Modarresi was born in [[Kuwait City|Kuwait]] in 1977. From his father's side, he is the son of [[Hadi al-Modarresi]], and great grandson of [[Mahdi Hussaini Shirazi|Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.modarresi.org/biography/index.html|title=al-Sirah al-Thatiya|last=|first=|date=|website=Office of Sayed Hadi Al-Modarresi|language=ar|trans-title=Biography|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> From his mother's side he is the grandson of Hashim al-Qazwini, and the great grandson of Muhammad-Sadiq al-Qazwini. He claims [[Sayyid|descent]] from the Prophet [[Muhammad]], through [[Ali ibn Husayn Zayn al-Abidin|Ali Ibn al-Husayn]] from his father, and [[Musa al-Kadhim]], from his mother.\n\nUnder his father's supervision, al-Modarresi followed a solid traditional curriculum in the [[hawza]], studying classical works on various disciplines of Islamic jurisprudence as well as the instrumental faculties commonly taught at religious learning institutions. A graduate of the acclaimed al-Qaim Theological Research Institute near the [[Sayyidah Zaynab Mosque]] in Damascus, al-Modarresi reached the level of Sotouh al Ulya (Upper Foundations). His classical curriculum embodied a methodology which crystallizes the middle way of Islam; respect for the differences between jurists, and a spiritual education drawn from the Qur'an and the traditions of [[Prophet Muhammad]] and his Household; the [[Ahlulbayt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nudba.com/wp/speakers/sayed-mahdi-modarresi/|title=Sayed Mahdi Modarresi|website=Nudba.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nHe also undertook his early academic education in the [[United States]], finally studying sociology, politics, and philosophy at tertiary level in [[Australia]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Activism ==\nal-Modarresi has criticised the atrocities committed by the Bahraini government against its people (namely the Shia), especially after the [[Bahraini uprising of 2011|uprising of 2011]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2010/09/10/bahrains-shia-crackdown/|title=Bahrain's Shia crackdown|last=Sotloff|first=Steven|website=Foreign Policy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> He believed that the country's mass uprising, was the result of many decades of abuse. al-Modarresi was also agitated by the West's silence to the situation in Bahrain, and writes in one his articles:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/the-staggers/2012/02/regime-bahrain-protesters|title=Isn't it time we backed Bahrain's revolution?|last=|first=|date=|website=NewStatesmen|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><blockquote>\"Whether western leaders decide to cut their losses or keep the Bahraini government on life support for the time being, by far the worst thing they can do is bury their heads in the sand and assume everything is going to be all right... Imagine the consequences if the western powers had sided with the Hosni Mubarak regime or that of Colonel Gaddafi until the very end... Had it not been for Saudi military support and the West\u2019s political backing, the truth is that this unelected [[House of Khalifa|Al Khalifa]] regime would have collapsed long ago\"</blockquote>al-Modarresi has also criticised [[Saudi Arabian government|Saudi Arabia]] and [[House of Saud|Al Saud]] for its human right's violations, and even so as to compare the regime to [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]], claiming the only real difference between ISIS and the Saudi regime is that the latter has 'made it', having secured a seat at the [[United Nations|UN]] and employ an army of flamboyant diplomats and lobbyists roaming the corridors of [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster Palace]] and [[Capitol Hill]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/sayed-mahdi-almodarresi/a-regime-known-for-its-re_b_11162286.html|title=A Regime Known for {{sic|It|'s|nolink=y}} Recklessness Just Made a Very Reckless Move|last=|first=|date=|website=Huffington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nal-Modarresi authored his first book in 1992, at the tender age of 15. This was a book in Arabic titled, \"About the Signs of Allah and His Greatness\". He later authored two more books in Arabic that were published in Beirut. His last Arabic book was an in-depth analytical study of the prophetic narration known as [[Hadith al-Thaqalayn]], which looks into the practical implications of this controversial narration and provides a thorough insight of the Shia-Sunni deliberations on this text.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109115447/http://ahlulbayt.tv/enlight/?page_id=6|title=Authors \u00ab Enlight Magazine|date=2013-11-09|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nIn the second decade of 2000, al-Modarresi shifted his attention to writing in English, and has published three books which are: \n\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Hajj: Rules and Rituals|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1515186021|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Our Beliefs: The Fundamental Tenets of Islam|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-0994240934|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The Lost Testament: What Christians Don't Know About Jesus|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en|asin=B01K170MDQ}}\n\nHe has also written a collection of essays regarding the contemporary challenges facing Muslim youth, with emphasis on problems which are more relevant in Western nations where they are a growing minority. Such 'taboo' subjects, such as pornography, alcohol, sex, drugs, and religious extremism are discussed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109115750/http://ahlulbayt.tv/enlight/?p=284|title=Raising a Family in the West \u00ab Enlight Magazine|date=2013-11-09|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Lectures==\nal-Modarressi delivers lectures worldwide on traditional as well as contemporary Islamic issues and has lectured in countless mosques, churches, universities, and seminaries across the globe. He has been interviewed by numerous news platforms and has appeared on TV and radio programs such as the BBC. An ardent advocate of interfaith dialogue,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109121823/http://ahlulbayt.tv/enlight/?p=545|title=Interfaith Dialogue at St. Andrew's \u00ab Enlight Magazine|date=2013-11-09|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> al-Modarresi engages in such events on a regular basis and has consistently spoken out against acts of terror.<ref>[http://www.modarresi.org/audio/english/ashura_attack.mp3 BBC's Reporting Religion Interviews - Sayed Mehdi al-Modarressi]</ref> He has also been adamant on directing the world's attention to the [[Arba'een Pilgrimage|Arbaeen pilgrimage]], calling the whole world to try and understand Hussein, his message, and his sacrifice, for this would allow them to begin to understand the ancient roots of ISIS and its credo of death and destruction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/sayed-mahdi-almodarresi/arbaeen-pilgrimage_b_6203756.html|title=World's Biggest Pilgrimage Now Underway, And Why You've Never Heard of it!|last=|first=|date=|website=Huffington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Sznajder|first=Micha\u0142 Jacenty|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SzMlDwAAQBAJ|title=Metropolitan Commuter Belt Tourism|date=2017-05-18|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=|isbn=978-1-317-06067-3|location=|pages=217|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://open.spotify.com/episode/6vv6gGxsWXxSOsc3619BuL|title=Husayn Means Beauty: The Attraction of the Seventh Century Martyr (1 of 2) (ENCORE) - Progressive Spirit|website=Spotify|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[http://www.modarresi.org/english/index.htm al-Modarresi's Official Website]\n*[https://twitter.com/sayedmodarresi Twitter page] (In English)\n*[https://twitter.com/thesayed Twitter page] (In Arabic)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFA